		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The board contains three big black things with pins comming out of them (sorry, i dont know what they are called.) </div>
<br />This is called a <em>chip</em> or an <em>integrated circuit</em>.
<br />In the particular case of NES carts, the big chips are ROMs, and the small is the CIC (lockout chip).
<br />
<br />Most european SMB carts are revised carts, wich have a A stampled on the back label of the cart. Those have a PRG ROM called "PAL-SM-0 PRG". The american carts have "NES-SM-0 PRG". I guess you got are rare early unrevised PAL cart who has a "NES-SM-0 PRG" PRG ROM as well, meaning it's basically the american version running on a PAL console. Nintendo decided later to fix music and gameplay speed to PAL and to release revised carts.
<br />At least that's what they did with Kid Icarus it seems, and it's likely what they did with SMB.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


