	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Oh, allright. Usually 'HVC' is for japan, 'NES' for america and 'PAL' for PAL territories, but when Nintendo re-used the ROM from a previous release they didn't change it's name.
<br />
<br />You are right the american version of SMB has all 'HVC' chips as the whole thing is untouched from japan, in fact only the cartridge case change but the ROM is exactly the same.
<br />Seems they released early PAL carts with a different case and lockout chip (meaning cart themselves cannot be interchanged), but with the exact same ROMs than japanese and american version. Because PAL hardware is different, it runs a 50Hz, meaning the whole game runs at 5/6th of the normal speed, and that the music is about one tone lower. Since SMB doesn't use raster effects, it runs fine on PAL even if it is slower so they didn't need to change anything. However for some reason they decided to addapt SMB to PAL region, fasting up the ROM and corrected the music pitch so that the result on a PAL console is similar to the result on a NTSC console. This cart is not a prototype, it's just an unrevised cart wich is most likely rarer than revised carts. Feel free to submit it to <a href="http://bootgod.dyndns.org:7777/home.php" class="postlink">bootgod's database</a> if you want, the database currently only have revised SMB carts.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


